    slug: "hidayat-al-qari-sharh-sahih-al-bukhari-10-volume-set-local",
    description: `Hidayat al-Qari Sharh Sahih al-Bukhari is a monumental ten-volume Urdu commentary on Sahih al-Bukhari, the most authentic collection of hadith in Islamic literature. This local Pakistani edition makes an essential scholarly work accessible to Urdu-speaking ulama, madrasah students, and serious students of Islamic knowledge at a fraction of the cost of imported Arabic commentaries.\n\nSahih al-Bukhari, compiled by Imam Muhammad bin Isma'il al-Bukhari (194–256 AH), contains 7,563 hadith selected from approximately 600,000 narrations that Imam al-Bukhari examined over sixteen years of travel and research. The "Hidayat al-Qari" commentary provides detailed explanations of each hadith, its chain of transmission (isnad), the circumstances under which it was narrated, linguistic analysis of key Arabic terms, and connections between related narrations within and across chapters. The commentary draws on the works of classical hadith scholars including Ibn Hajar al-Asqalani's "Fath al-Bari" and Badr al-Din al-Ayni's "Umdat al-Qari," distilling their insights into accessible Urdu prose.\n\nEach volume covers specific books (kutub) of Sahih al-Bukhari, beginning with the Book of Revelation and proceeding through purification, prayer, pilgrimage, marriage, trade, Jihad, and the virtues of the Prophet and his companions. The commentary addresses apparent contradictions between narrations, provides biographical information about the narrators in each chain, and explains the methodological principles Imam al-Bukhari used in selecting and organizing his hadith. This makes the set an invaluable resource for understanding not just the content of individual hadith but the broader science of hadith scholarship.\n\nThe ten-volume set is produced with durable binding and clear typography suitable for extended study sessions in madrasahs and personal libraries. It serves as a primary reference for ulama preparing khutbahs, teachers delivering hadith classes, and students preparing for examinations in hadith sciences. For Urdu-speaking Muslims who want to engage deeply with the primary sources of Islamic knowledge, this commentary set provides an essential bridge between the original Arabic text and comprehensive understanding.`,
